WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.800
About two years ago, I started at Riskified, an e-commerce fraud prevention company based

00:00:10.800 --> 00:00:16.480
in Tel Aviv, Israel. Previously, I'd worked with ecological and environmental sciences

00:00:16.480 --> 00:00:24.920
data. I'd worked with a lot of different kinds of files, shapefiles, XML, CSVs of course,

00:00:24.920 --> 00:00:29.240
sometimes thousands at a time, but I hadn't really gotten the chance to work so much with

00:00:29.240 --> 00:00:34.520
databases. So I was really excited to enter a world where there were millions of orders

00:00:34.520 --> 00:00:40.680
coming in each day. There were teams dedicated to setting up ETLs to process that incoming

00:00:40.680 --> 00:00:46.279
data and get it neat and tidy into databases for me. And all I had to do is query that

00:00:46.279 --> 00:00:54.560
data into R and start playing. And I was excited because, you know, I had R under my belt and

00:00:54.560 --> 00:01:00.639
R was a super multi-tool. It seemed to be able to do almost anything. I used it to create

00:01:00.639 --> 00:01:07.360
slides and websites. I used it for querying APIs and even building APIs. You know, it

00:01:07.360 --> 00:01:13.239
did a lot for what was, you know, supposedly just this statistical tool. SQL, on the other

00:01:13.239 --> 00:01:20.080
hand, was a little bit more like a screwdriver. It's a perfectly fine tool, but it seems to

00:01:20.080 --> 00:01:28.639
be only really good at one thing, which is to query databases. And so going to RISCified,

00:01:28.639 --> 00:01:34.000
in my mind was a little bit of this feeling of, why bother to learn SQL if I can just

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:41.320
use R for everything? One reason I was fairly confident is because I knew about this package

00:01:41.320 --> 00:01:48.040
called dbplyr, which is an extension of dplyr that runs on databases. So instead of running

00:01:48.040 --> 00:01:54.120
something on a data frame in your R session, you're actually running it on a table in a

00:01:54.120 --> 00:01:59.599
database, but it feels like it's just a data frame. And what it's doing is it's taking

00:01:59.599 --> 00:02:05.160
your tidy RISC code, translating it into SQL, sending it off to the database, bringing it

00:02:05.160 --> 00:02:11.479
back, and then giving you this, you know, table output like you're used to, as if everything

00:02:11.479 --> 00:02:20.479
all happened locally. And so if we look at how this works, let's just take a simple R

00:02:20.479 --> 00:02:27.160
example where I have now an empty cars table in its database. I take some variable miles

00:02:27.160 --> 00:02:33.520
per gallon, round it, create this new variable, and then I select two other variables, this

00:02:33.520 --> 00:02:40.320
rounded miles per gallon, and then horsepower. If I look at the translation, it also looks

00:02:40.320 --> 00:02:46.600
fairly good. It looks somewhat similar to the R code. I'm rounding it, I get the horsepower

00:02:46.600 --> 00:02:53.279
from empty cars, the table. If I were to have written this out by hand, I probably wouldn't

00:02:53.279 --> 00:03:00.919
write in the backticks, but otherwise it looks almost the same. And sometimes using dbplyr

00:03:00.919 --> 00:03:07.080
really saves you a lot of kind of tedious work. For example, if I want all columns except for

00:03:07.080 --> 00:03:13.960
horsepower, I can use this simple expression in dplyr, and then it generates the SQL code

00:03:13.960 --> 00:03:23.320
where I literally have to write out every single column except for horsepower. If I want to now

00:03:23.320 --> 00:03:29.800
take the maximum across all of the different columns, I can also do it very easily in dbplyr.

00:03:29.800 --> 00:03:36.679
It's just one line of code, and then it's able to generate this really long and very repetitive

00:03:36.679 --> 00:03:43.399
query for me. It's not a hard query to write, but you know, it does take some effort, and it is very

00:03:43.399 --> 00:03:53.000
repetitive. But the thing is, over time you also realize that, you know, what you're used to doing

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:58.759
in just regular dplyr isn't always going to work when you're connected to a database. For example,

00:03:58.759 --> 00:04:07.720
if I now want to look at the number of NAs or nulls across every single column, I can, you know,

00:04:07.720 --> 00:04:15.800
use this one liner in R. If I try to do the same thing on a table, it will say no such column dot x.

00:04:17.480 --> 00:04:21.799
It's angry at me because I'm trying to use an anonymous function, and it doesn't know how to

00:04:21.799 --> 00:04:28.119
translate the anonymous function. So what I have to do is I have to fix this set of commands.

00:04:28.119 --> 00:04:34.679
I have to break it up into the individual steps, which is isna first, and then the sum, and now it'll work.

00:04:36.920 --> 00:04:44.519
Well, now it'll work for some databases, and this is where it kind of becomes

00:04:44.519 --> 00:04:51.000
complicated a little bit. On the one hand, dbplyr saves you kind of the mental load of

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:55.399
learning SQL, this whole new language, but on the other hand, you still have to realize that you're

00:04:55.399 --> 00:05:01.399
working with databases. It does a lot of the translations to dialects for you, but you have to

00:05:01.399 --> 00:05:07.720
know what is specific to your database. In some databases, for example, isna becomes a boolean.

00:05:08.279 --> 00:05:15.320
In other databases, isna becomes an integer, and depending on what you're using, you might have

00:05:15.320 --> 00:05:19.399
to convert it into an integer in order to sum it up because it can't sum up booleans.

00:05:20.359 --> 00:05:25.959
And so you have to make sure to still juggle that information in your mind as you're using

00:05:25.959 --> 00:05:32.359
dbplyr. So you are using something you're used to, but you can't use it exactly in the way that

00:05:33.720 --> 00:05:40.839
you normally would. And so over time, I did really start to appreciate SQL, the screwdriver,

00:05:41.640 --> 00:05:46.359
because even they have their moments, and you know, sometimes it is easier to just switch over to a

00:05:46.359 --> 00:05:52.839
different language rather than to try to juggle how regular dplyr is different from like dbplyr

00:05:54.359 --> 00:06:04.600
code on this specific database. And so for example, if I take what I had from before,

00:06:04.600 --> 00:06:08.519
I switch out the ending, and now I have a group by and summarize instead.

00:06:09.959 --> 00:06:14.600
If I were to write this out by hand, it's also a fairly simple SQL query. The ordering is a

00:06:14.600 --> 00:06:19.720
little bit different, but otherwise it has all the same components. If I now take the

00:06:19.720 --> 00:06:27.320
machine translation of this, it looks a little bit scary at first. It's going to run just fine.

00:06:27.320 --> 00:06:31.880
It's just as efficient. It's not going to have any problems, but you can see that it's not as

00:06:31.880 --> 00:06:38.600
readable. It's harder to distinguish what here is really important, what is just kind of extra

00:06:39.559 --> 00:06:45.000
code that is used to generate this, to automatically generate this query.

00:06:46.119 --> 00:06:51.480
And so at some point, once you have to, you know, hand SQL code off to someone else,

00:06:51.480 --> 00:06:56.200
or if you need to really optimize for speed, and you need to kind of input some of these

00:06:56.200 --> 00:07:02.440
little database tricks that you know about, you have to dig into the SQL. There's just no way

00:07:02.440 --> 00:07:09.239
around it. And for me, it's kind of like using Google Translate. I live in Israel. I did not

00:07:09.239 --> 00:07:17.320
grow up speaking Hebrew. You know, I learned the alphabet just a few years ago. And I can get around

00:07:17.320 --> 00:07:25.720
with just Google Translate. I can survive. But you also really quickly realize that it doesn't,

00:07:26.519 --> 00:07:32.679
you can't express yourself exactly in the way that you want to. You lose out on a lot of the

00:07:32.679 --> 00:07:39.399
nuances of the language. Sometimes you even have to alter the way you input your English sentence

00:07:39.399 --> 00:07:42.119
in order for the translation to come out okay on the other side.

00:07:44.440 --> 00:07:51.000
Speaking of language, that's one other really amazing thing about SQL. It's kind of this

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:58.920
lingua franca among at least like the technical folks in a company. Of course, the database

00:07:58.920 --> 00:08:03.320
administrators are familiar with it, but also business analysts, data scientists,

00:08:03.320 --> 00:08:09.320
software developers, everyone has at least that core level of SQL. So if you need to communicate

00:08:09.320 --> 00:08:15.239
some actions you want to do to data, this is a really good way to communicate that through code.

00:08:16.200 --> 00:08:21.799
And so with time, I realized really that R and SQL belong in the same toolkit. You can survive

00:08:21.799 --> 00:08:28.279
on just one or the other. But over time, it's really nice to be able to use both very well,

00:08:28.279 --> 00:08:32.840
especially if you're in this intersection of using R and databases.

00:08:35.479 --> 00:08:41.239
The nice thing is if you know one, it's fairly easy to become bilingual. If you look at just

00:08:41.880 --> 00:08:47.000
the main verbs, for example, in each of the two languages, you see there's a lot of overlap.

00:08:47.960 --> 00:08:54.359
Select is select, group by is group by. There are some things you have to learn. You have to

00:08:54.359 --> 00:09:00.599
realize filters, now where or having in SQL. Arrange is order by, and so on and so forth. So

00:09:00.599 --> 00:09:04.520
there is a little bit of translation you have to do, but it's not too big of a leap.

00:09:04.679 --> 00:09:10.599
And the other thing is if you're used to R, then you know that you kind of write things out in the

00:09:10.599 --> 00:09:16.359
order that they happen. So let's say I have a table, I filter by some condition. Okay,

00:09:16.359 --> 00:09:23.880
now I group by some column and get a summarized aggregate column, and then I filter by that column,

00:09:23.880 --> 00:09:27.479
for example, and then I can arrange by something.

00:09:27.559 --> 00:09:32.760
And then I filter by that column, for example, and then I can arrange by something.

00:09:34.599 --> 00:09:40.119
If I were to write this out in SQL, I would have to, I would start with, yeah, the table,

00:09:40.119 --> 00:09:45.799
the condition, group by. Now the select or the summarize jumps all the way up to the top.

00:09:47.559 --> 00:09:54.039
Having is at the bottom again. Order by is also at the bottom. And so you have to kind of remember

00:09:54.039 --> 00:09:58.039
that the ordering is a little bit different. You don't necessarily write things in the order

00:09:58.039 --> 00:10:04.760
that you would do them. But other than that, it's something that you get used to fairly quickly.

00:10:06.520 --> 00:10:11.640
And if you're like me and you spend a lot of time in RStudio, the nice thing is there are

00:10:11.640 --> 00:10:16.599
a lot of SQL things you can do from within that familiar environment of RStudio,

00:10:18.119 --> 00:10:23.640
especially with the newer versions of the IDE. For example, if you open up a SQL file,

00:10:23.640 --> 00:10:28.760
you have your nice, you know, colors, syntax, highlighting, so you can see what the verbs are,

00:10:28.760 --> 00:10:35.719
what the, you know, the table names are. What I didn't realize for the longest time is there's

00:10:35.719 --> 00:10:40.119
this line at the top that says, you know, exclamation mark preview with some stuff after

00:10:40.119 --> 00:10:44.200
that. And this is where you can actually set a connection. So if you set a connection to the

00:10:44.200 --> 00:10:50.679
database, you can get the SQL preview pane where you can preview that SQL query within RStudio.

00:10:51.320 --> 00:10:54.280
This took me a while to figure out, but it's a really nice feature.

00:10:56.599 --> 00:11:01.559
R Markdown is this kind of magical document where you can mix all kinds of different languages,

00:11:01.559 --> 00:11:07.640
and R and SQL is no exception. You'll start probably with some kind of YAML header like usual.

00:11:08.280 --> 00:11:14.679
You might have an R setup chunk where you have packages, the database connection, maybe you'll

00:11:14.679 --> 00:11:20.840
set up a table like I did here, and then you can have your SQL query. And if you have this inline

00:11:20.840 --> 00:11:28.840
mode enabled, you can actually see those previews within R Markdown and work with both R and SQL

00:11:28.840 --> 00:11:36.200
interactively within this one document. And finally, you can navigate through your database

00:11:36.200 --> 00:11:43.159
from within R. You can see what databases you have, schemas, tables, columns within tables,

00:11:43.880 --> 00:11:46.679
all within that RStudio interface.

00:11:49.960 --> 00:11:55.400
And so I've talked a lot about all these cool things about R and SQL together, but what does

00:11:55.400 --> 00:12:01.320
that look like in real life? I wish I knew more about what people are doing in the wider world,

00:12:01.960 --> 00:12:07.640
out in the wild, so to speak, but I can only really speak to my experience and the experience

00:12:07.640 --> 00:12:14.520
of my colleagues at Riskified. On a regular day, I'm often switching between a SQL IDE and RStudio.

00:12:15.559 --> 00:12:21.080
I did just talk about all these SQL things you can do with RStudio, but some are still not quite

00:12:21.080 --> 00:12:27.799
that mature, and so I really like using the SQL IDE for all of the extra auto-formatting,

00:12:27.799 --> 00:12:32.520
highlighting, code and field suggestions, so I don't have to remember those long table names

00:12:33.080 --> 00:12:41.080
just from memory. One other thing is that it's really easy to stop bad queries in a dedicated

00:12:41.080 --> 00:12:46.840
IDE. Sometimes an RStudio gets stuck, and I press on that red button for ages, and in the end,

00:12:46.840 --> 00:12:56.919
I have to just force quit my RStudio and just start over. On the RStudio side, there are a lot

00:12:56.919 --> 00:13:02.919
of nice R features, obviously visualizations, reporting, being able to mix languages in the

00:13:02.919 --> 00:13:08.760
same document, as we mentioned earlier, but I think maybe most importantly, you have this ability to

00:13:08.760 --> 00:13:14.760
organize your analysis project, and on top of that, have version control. That means you have your,

00:13:14.760 --> 00:13:20.520
you know, you have your SQL files, your data files, your R file, maybe R Markdown files,

00:13:20.520 --> 00:13:26.760
all together in one space. It's a project that you can now easily give to someone else and have

00:13:26.760 --> 00:13:32.280
them work on it and have everything work, and on top of that, everything is version controlled,

00:13:32.280 --> 00:13:36.280
so you can connect directly to GitHub and have it all sit there as well.

00:13:38.520 --> 00:13:45.000
And so, speaking of project structure, if you were to, you know, take a walk through the GitHub

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:51.880
repositories at Riskified, you would often encounter some kind of folder structure like this,

00:13:52.440 --> 00:13:58.200
where you have SQL files, where you're reading in relevant data, doing some initial data processing,

00:13:58.200 --> 00:14:04.359
and getting that initial sample population ready for analysis, and then you have your R files,

00:14:04.359 --> 00:14:11.400
where you do that, all the complex steps, the stats, visualizations, etc. Sometimes you're bringing

00:14:11.400 --> 00:14:14.840
extra information from the database in between with smaller queries,

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:20.919
and then finally, you have this R Markdown report, where you share your results and

00:14:20.919 --> 00:14:25.640
conclusions with stakeholders, and this is where both of those pieces really come together

00:14:25.640 --> 00:14:31.400
into this one final product. And because we're using R and SQL so much within Riskified, we

00:14:31.400 --> 00:14:38.599
actually have a dedicated package to handle those database connections and also just add little

00:14:38.599 --> 00:14:46.200
helpers that help us with our day-to-day flow. For example, we keep all our configurations within

00:14:46.200 --> 00:14:52.280
this package. You know, anything that's not too sensitive, like a host name, port, etc., we just

00:14:52.280 --> 00:14:58.200
stick into the package. If we need to update it, we just update it in that one place, and as long

00:14:58.200 --> 00:15:06.039
as people reinstall the package, it gets updated across all the computers. The other thing is that

00:15:06.039 --> 00:15:12.119
we basically just use one database, at least among the analytical teams, and so unless you

00:15:12.840 --> 00:15:19.239
explicitly provide a database connection, we assume we know what you want,

00:15:20.119 --> 00:15:24.200
and so that's built into our very own getQuery function.

00:15:26.679 --> 00:15:33.320
There was one point recently where we actually had to migrate from one database to another.

00:15:33.320 --> 00:15:38.919
It was a bit of a slog, but one thing that did help smooth it over a little bit

00:15:38.919 --> 00:15:44.520
was this option we added to switch between the old database or the new database. You just had

00:15:44.520 --> 00:15:49.960
to do it once at the beginning of your R session and it would last for all of your getQuery, so

00:15:49.960 --> 00:15:55.960
you didn't have to go in and now start changing your code to specify the database connection for

00:15:55.960 --> 00:16:05.719
every single query in your code. One small thing that we do a lot also is caching query results.

00:16:06.200 --> 00:16:15.159
The first time you ask the database directly, the second time it will have stored the result

00:16:15.159 --> 00:16:23.479
in some temporary file. It's cached, ready for reading, and unless you force it to

00:16:23.479 --> 00:16:28.440
connect to the database again, you have a much quicker response the second time around,

00:16:28.440 --> 00:16:31.640
and that saves a lot of time as you're iterating through your analysis.

00:16:32.359 --> 00:16:36.760
And finally, we also have other little helpers like access to pipelines for bringing large

00:16:36.760 --> 00:16:43.320
amounts of data from R to the database or the other way around. Sometimes insert statements

00:16:43.320 --> 00:16:49.159
just don't cut it, and you need to, for us, what is easier is to dump the data into some

00:16:49.159 --> 00:16:53.960
cloud storage and then bring it directly into the database or going the other way around.

00:16:54.599 --> 00:17:01.320
And so to conclude, R and SQL, they both have their strengths. R is great for summarization

00:17:01.320 --> 00:17:06.920
of cost columns, especially, you know, selecting specific columns, translations to multiple

00:17:06.920 --> 00:17:13.319
dialects, if you're working with several databases. SQL, on the other hand, is great for,

00:17:14.439 --> 00:17:19.000
like, is really needed when you need to optimize for speed or readability because you're having

00:17:19.560 --> 00:17:32.280
it off to another team to review that code. And, you know, there's still a lot to learn, I'm sure.

00:17:32.280 --> 00:17:39.959
I'm still on this journey of learning how to use R and SQL well together, but I would love to also

00:17:39.959 --> 00:17:46.920
hear from you. Is your story similar, different from mine? My contact details are here, and thank

00:17:46.920 --> 00:17:56.199
you so much for listening today.

